'''''Carnivàle''''', pronounced /{{IPA|kɑɹ.nɪ'væl}}/ ("car-nih-VAL"),<ref>Per DVD audio commantaries by producers</ref> is an [[United States|American]] dramatic [[television series]] produced by [[Home Box Office|HBO]] and ran for two seasons between 2003 and 2005. The show was created by [[Daniel Knauf]], and starred [[Nick Stahl]] and [[Clancy Brown]]. It won 5 Emmys in 2004.

The series is a period drama set in the [[United States]] during the [[Great Depression]] and follows the lives of two very different groups of people. It has an overarching story about the battle between [[good]] and [[evil]] as well as the struggle between [[free will]] and [[destiny]], and mixes [[Christianity|Christian]] theology with aspects of [[gnosticism]] and [[Freemasonry|Masonic]] lore, particularly that of the [[Knights Templar]].

==Conception==

''Carnivàle'' creator [[Daniel Knauf]] conceived the initial script for the ''Carnivàle'' pilot in 1991, thirteen years before the shooting of the series began.<ref name=chat_milfay>{{cite web |url=http://www.savecarnivale.org/html/carniecast_071705.htm |title=Highlights from the Dan Knauf Chat - Episode 1 - Milfay |date=[[July 17]], [[2005]] |publisher=savecarnivale.org |accessdate=2007-07-28}}</ref><ref name=variety_creation>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117906608.html?categoryid=1734&cs=1 |title=''Carnivale'' - Where mysticism's often meted out in meticulously slow fashion |date=[[June 16]], [[2004]] |publisher=variety.com |accessdate=2007-07-28}}</ref> During this time, Knauf worked sporadically in [[Hollywood]] but mainly earned his living with jobs such as in the insurance business, so his experience in the film and television business was not very developed. The ''Carnivàle'' script, originally intended to be a feature script, was one of his first scripts.<ref name=variety_creation /> Despite his other involvements, Knauf continued to tweak the script in the following years and plotted the broad strokes of the story from the beginning so that he knew where ''Carnivàle'' would head, up to the last scene of the show. A certain amount of flexibility was always considered.<ref name=chat_milfay /><ref name=yahoo_msg11817>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/11817 Daniel Knauf at Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[February 21]], [[2005]]). Relevant parts mirrored at [http://z6.invisionfree.com/The_Baggage_Trailer/index.php?showtopic=158 The Baggage Trailer Forum]. Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref>

In 2001, Daniel Knauf decided to part from the feature business and forwarded the ''Carnivàle'' script as a TV script to [[Howard Klein]] via a mutal friend, [[Scott Winant]].<ref name=variety_creation /><ref name=dvd_museum>''The Museum of Television & Radio's William S. Paley Television Festival CARNIVALE'' (March 16, 2004). Part of the ''Carnivàle'' Season 2 DVD Special Features.</ref> Klein then brought it to the attention of [[HBO]], who were receptive immediately.<ref name=dvd_museum /> The pilot episode was shot over a period of twenty-one days. Once the show got greenlit, additional material, mainly on Brother Justin's side, was shot.<ref name=chat_milfay />

Knauf had originally designed Brother Justin as a preacher far along in his career as well as a recurring instead of a regular character. But after seeing the prelimary pilot, Knauf and his group of producers realized that there was nowhere to go with him in a television series. So they decided to make Brother Justin an ordinary Methodist minister in a little town, setting him back in time for about a year or two. This opened new possibilities, and the character of Iris was created as a supporting character around him.<ref name carni_iw_jan04>{{cite web |url=http://carnivaleinterviews.blogspot.com/2004_01_01_archive.html |title=Interview with Daniel Knauf - Part 1 |date=[[January 12]], [[2004]] |publisher=Beth Blighton at carnivaleinterviews.blogspot.com |accessdate=2007-07-29}}</ref>

Little was changed on Ben Hawkins' side. The Dreifuss family was only added after a ''Carnivàle'' consultant told the producers about his research of families managing cooch shows, which fascinated them.<ref name carni_iw_jan04 />

==Format==

The ''Carnivàle'' story was originally intended to take place over three "cycles," each lasting two seasons, for a total of six seasons.<ref name=hbo_msg683555>[http://boards.hbo.com/thread.jspa?threadID=300000617&messageID=300683555#300683555 Daniel Knauf (fboffo) at HBO forums] ([[April 17]], [[2005]]). Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref> This plan was abruptly changed when HBO cancelled the show after only two seasons, although the first two seasons of Carnivale still make up one finished "book."

Each season consists of thirteen episodes, describing the events in the lives of two characters who have yet to meet. Although almost each episode has a distiniguished story that may qualify as a separate entity, all episodes are parts of an overarching [[Good and evil|good-versus-evil]] story that only culminates and resolves very late in Season 2. Show creator [[Daniel Knauf]] stated that ''Carnivàle'' was written to be open to interpretation, including the interpretation of the writer.<ref name=yahoo_msg11232>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/11232 Daniel Knauf at Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[February 11]], [[2005]]). Relevant parts mirrored at [http://z6.invisionfree.com/The_Baggage_Trailer/index.php?showtopic=158 The Baggage Trailer Forum]. Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref> Many television critics praised the depth of plot, story and atmosphere, and the show build a cult following, but it was not able to generate a big interest among the average TV audience.<ref name=variety_cancellation>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117922539.html?categoryid=1417&cs=1&s=h&p=0 |title=''Carnivale'' packing up |date=[[May 11]], [[2005]] |publisher=variety.com |accessdate=2007-07-25}}</ref>

