==Cancellation and future==
{{seealso|Fictional universe of Carnivàle#Open questions}}

''Carnivàle'' drew 5.3 million viewers for its premiere and finished the first season with 3.5 million viewers.<ref name=variety_creation /> During the second season, the ratings slowly rose toward the end, but the show became increasingly expensive to produce.<ref name=zap2it /> [[HBO]] however traditionally carries many of its shows through to an end, so the future of ''Carnivàle'' beyond Season 2 was not clear. Since HBO makes their commitments only for one year at a time, a new Season 3 would have meant to open up a new two-season book in Daniel Knauf's six-year plan, including introducing new storylines for the current characters as well as for new characters, and further clarifying and elaborating on the show's mythology.<ref name=yahoo_msg17804>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/17804 Daniel Knauf at Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[April 1]], [[2005]]). Relevant parts mirrored at [http://z6.invisionfree.com/The_Baggage_Trailer/index.php?showtopic=158 The Baggage Trailer Forum]. Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref> 

Although many fans had assumed that the show would be renewed, it was leaked in early May 2005 that the series would not be returning for a third season.<ref name=yahoo_msg19860>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/19860 Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[May 7]], [[2005]]). Mirrored at [http://forums.dvdfile.com/showthread.php?t=53930 forums.dvdfile.com]. Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref> HBO confirmed that the show had been cancelled on May 11, 2005.<ref name=variety_cancellation /> HBO's president [[Chris Albrecht]] stated that HBO would have considered otherwise if the producers had been willing to lower the price of an episode to US$2 million. But the costs for the size of the cast, the all-on location shooting and the number of episodes per season were too enormous for them.<ref name=zap2it />

The cancellation left several plotlines unfinished and outraged many viewers. Some of them organized petitions and mailing drives to HBO in an effort to get the show renewed. This generated more than 50,000 emails to the network in a single weekend.<ref name=zap2it>{{cite web |url=http://tv.zap2it.com/tveditorial/tve_main/1,1002,271%7C96426%7C1%7C,00.html |title='Carnivale' Fans Besiege HBO with E-mails |date=[[July 18]], [[2005]] |publisher=zap2it.com |accessdate=2007-07-25}}</ref> Show creator Daniel Knauf told fans that such moves would likely not prove very successful, and that HBO would not reconsider their cancellation announcement anytime soon.<ref name=chat_milfay /> He doubted that HBO would want to sell the show or allow it to air on a competing network, and since HBO owns the characters as well as the plot, Knauf would not be allowed not spin off his story into a new form or medium without HBO's permission.<ref name=yahoo_msg18916>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/18916 Daniel Knauf at Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[April 17]], [[2005]]). Relevant parts mirrored at [http://z6.invisionfree.com/The_Baggage_Trailer/index.php?showtopic=158 The Baggage Trailer Forum]. Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref>

Daniel Knauf predicted though that, given a strong enough fan base, HBO's own plans might change in the future, possibly switching ''Carnivàle'' to another medium.<ref name=chat_milfay /> At the same time, Knauf made it explicitly clear that tying up loose ends via a three-hour movie was not an option for him, and that he would refuse to participate if one was made. Knauf was not willing to sacrifice his story material that was enough to have ''Carnivàle'' go for four more seasons, and he would rather "leave Carnivale unfinished than finished poorly."<ref name=yahoo_msg18916 /><ref>Canceled (for now) - Die-hards fight to save TV faves. The Washington Times ([[July 29]], [[2005]]). Mirrored at [http://www.savecarnivale.org/html/tommydolan_washtimes.htm savecarnival.org]. Retrieved on [[july 28]], [[2007]].</ref>

Knauf would not release a quick run-down of intended future plots, and explained his reasons with the needed collaboration with other writers, the directors, and the actors. He however answered a few basic details about the immediate fate of major characters, who were left hanging after Season 2's cliffhanger,<ref name=yahoo_msg20373>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/20373 Daniel Knauf at Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[May 12]], [[2005]]). Relevant parts mirrored at [http://z6.invisionfree.com/The_Baggage_Trailer/index.php?showtopic=158 The Baggage Trailer Forum]. Retrieved on [[July 28]], [[2007]].</ref> and provided in-depth information regarding the underlying fictional laws of nature that the writers had not been able to fully explore in the first two seasons.

As of July 2007, no news have come up about HBO reviving ''Carnivàle'' except for a February 2006 mediavillage.com article; it stated that [[HBO]] may be considering developing a movie or miniseries that would wrap up many of these plot lines to be telecast in 2007. A resurrection of the franchise as an ongoing series was also deemed possible for 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mediavillage.com/jmentr/2006/02/09/jmer-02-09-06/ |title=Fans May See More of ''Arrested Development'' and ''Carnivale'' |date=[[February 9]], [[2006]] |publisher=mediavillage.com |accessdate=2007-07-25}}</ref> This seems very unlikely now.

==Lawsuit==

On [[June 9]], [[2005]], a lawsuit was filed in United States District court by writer Jeff Bergquist. Mr. Bergquist claimed that the creators of ''Carnivàle'' did not originate the idea for the show, but rather stole it from his unpublished novel ''Beulah''. Mr. Bergquist claimed that HBO and ''Carnivàle'' creator Daniel Knauf violated his copyright on ''Beulah'' and sought both recognition and punitive damages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/05178/528920.stm |title=TV Notes: 'Carnivale' copied? |date=[[June 27]], [[2005]] |publisher=post-gazette.com |accessdate=2007-07-28}}</ref> The case was [[Prejudice (law)|dismissed with prejudice]] on [[February 17]], [[2006]].{{dubious|date=July 2007}}

== Reception ==

=== Critical reviews===

Many early reviews gave ''Carnivàle'' good marks but also stated that its unique characters and story might prevent it from becoming a huge main stream audience success.<ref name=cnn /> ''[[Daily Variety]]''  TV editor Joseph Adalian predicted that "it will get mostly positive reviews but some people will be put off by the general weirdness of the show."<ref name=cnn>{{cite web | last=Doty | first=Meriah | title=Taking a tour with 'Carnivale' | url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/TV/09/11/sprj.caf03.carnivale/ | date=[[September 11]], [[2003]] | publisher = cnn.com | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> Phil Gallo of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described ''Carnivàle'' as "an absolute visual stunner with compelling freak-show characters -- but the series unfortunately takes a leisurely approach toward getting to a point,"<ref name=vareity_review1>{{cite web | last=Gallo | first=Phil | title=Recently Reviewed - Carnivale | url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117921817.html?categoryid=32&cs=1 | date=[[September 11]], [[2003]] | publisher=variety.com | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> whereas James Poniewozik of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called the first three episodes "frustrating" as well as "spellbinding."<ref name=time.com>{{cite web | last=Poniewozik | first=James | title = HBO's Cirque du So-So | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,483299,00.html | date=[[September 7]], [[2003]] | publisher=time.com | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> Amanda Murray of BBC said "With so little revealed, it's almost impossible to pass judgment on the show - it's hard to tell if this is just good, or going to be great."<ref name=bbc>{{cite web | last=Murray | first=Amanda | title=Review: Carnivale | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/news/cult/2004/09/13/14282.shtml | date=[[September 13]], [[2004]] | publisher=bbc.co.uk | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> 

Later DVD reviews were able to judge the series on the basis of full seasons. While the acting, set design, costuming, art direction and cinematography continued to be praised,<ref name=dvdtalk /><ref name=ugo>{{cite web | last=Enk | first=Bryan | title=Carnivale: Season Two (HBO) | url=http://www.ugo.com/channels/filmtv/features/carnivaleseasontwo/review.asp | publisher=ugo.com | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> some reviewers disfavored the writing (especially of Season 1) as "lack[ing] story momentum"<ref name=ugo /> or as "sometimes gripping but mostly boring."<ref>{{cite web | last=Chaw | first=Walter | title=Carnivàle: The Complete First Season | url=http://filmfreakcentral.net/dvdreviews/carnivale.htm | publisher=filmfreakcentral.net | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref> Other reviewers pointed out that ''Carnivàle'' may "demand more from its audience than many are willing to invest. [...] Without paying close attention, it's tempting to assume that the show is unnecessarily cryptic and misleading."<ref name=dvdtalk /> ''Carnivale'''s story was also surveyed as long and complex, "and if you don't start from the beginning, you'll be completely lost."<ref name=dreadcentral>{{cite web | last=Kasch | first=Andrew | title = Carnivale: The Complete Second Season (DVD) | url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/index.php?name=Reviews&req=showcontent&id=1066 | date=[[September 8]], [[2006]] | publisher=deadcentral.com | accessdate=2007-07-31}}</ref>

=== Fandom ===

As ''Carnivàle'' slowly grew and matured during its first season, the series gained a respectable following of dedicated viewers as typical for many [[cult television]] series.<ref name=ugo /><ref name=dreadcentral /> ''Carnivàle'' fans usually referred to themselves as "Carnies" and arranged [http://www.carnycon.com/ Carny Con] fan conventions in 2005 and 2006 after the series had gotten cancelled.

Show creator [[Daniel Knauf]] actively participated in online fandom and offered story-related clues to fans who wanted to dive deeper into the mythology of the show. He also gave insight into reasons for the show's cancellation in 2005 before he even spoke to the press.<ref name=yahoo_msg20320>[http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO/message/20320 Daniel Knauf at Yahoo Carnivale HBO] (registration required) ([[May 12]], [[2005]]). Mirrored at [http://savecarnivale.blogspot.com/2005/05/dan-knauf-speaks-about-carnivales.html savecarnivale.blogspot.com]. Retrieved on [[July 31]], [[2007]].</ref> By July 2007, he is still in contact with the show's fandom and posts semi-regularly in ''Carnivàle'' messageboards.<ref>{{cite newsgroup | title =Yahoo Carnivale HBO | url = http://tv.groups.yahoo.com/group/CarnivaleHBO }}</ref>

